  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Ralph Waldo Emerson refused to lecture before the New Bedford Lyceum when he learned of the colored people&apos;s expulsion &quot;from their accustomed privileges of being received as members&quot; of the Lyceum. Mary Merrick Brooks thinks the enemies of the colored people may try to keep Mr. Emerson&apos;s refusal a secret. Mary M. Brooks offers the services of a Miss Jervis of Concord to Caroline Weston at the Boston anti-slavery fair.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Also enclosed is a print (visual work) of Ralph Waldo Emerson, 1854, artist unknown. It is a head-and-shoulders portrait of Emerson facing right. Handwritten in pencil beneath the image, is: &quot;Emerson, Vol. I.&quot;</subfield>
